I’m so excited to see where #MoonKnight  lands in the grand tapestry of the MCU. I’m already excited for his next appearance and hope he plays a very large part going forward in this new era of heroes. As an Oscar Isaac stan-in-bfflaw I’m so thrilled this series is THIS good.

This is such a grand scale origin story for #MoonKnight , and it’s absolutely what the character deserved. The mysterious journey that we’re taken along on as we learn about Marc (and Steven) is enthralling. One of the strongest origins to date

I love the format they’ve chosen to present Marc/#MoonKnight  with and, as expected, Oscar Isaac blows it away. Completely. Few could have done what Isaac has with this character, his enigmatic charisma and fine-tuned expertise bring Marc to life so captivatingly.

Got to watch the first 4 episodes of #MoonKnight  and it blew all of my expectations away. I certainly wasn’t expecting them to go THIS hard, but they did. It’s funny, it’s eerie, it’s brutal. It’s SO much fun and a fresh, new take for a Marvel property

All that to say this, this is the last day(s) of my Moon Knight fandom innocence. I welcome everyone into the #MoonKnight fold. I hope the show is great and it encourages more people to go out and seek out the comics. 

Praise Khonshu🌙

#MoonKnight has never really fit in, despite trying his hardest to do so. He’s a black sheep, he’s the guy that other characters snicker about when he’s around, he’s odd, & he marches to the beat of his own drum because he believes what he is doing is the RIGHT thing

Moon Knight has always been the closest thing that encapsulated me in comic book form. I don’t mean the DID, or the resurrection by an Egyptian God, or the violence, or the ‘toe the line’ mentality or any of the other comic book stuff, even though those things are super rad

There is a sort of innocence that I am losing in being “the Moon Knight” guy. This isn’t a bad thing. My love and knowledge for the character doesn’t dissipate just because he will be the center of the zeitgeist. Quite the opposite actually.

I’ve read comics for as long as I could read & comprehend them. I love comics and I love lots of characters, but discovering Moon Knight was life changing. It set my life on a course of fandom I could never have fathomed. I found a guy that “nobody” knew. And he became my guy.

With that being said, I have always flew the Moon Knight flag very proudly. This is might be the last time, outside of creating my own thing, that I will feel this way, as in these fleeting moments before the world is introduced to wacky world of Marc Spector & friends

This is significant for me because for the majority of my life, #MoonKnight has always been MY guy. Granted, I do not own the character & I sure as hell didn’t create him. I’ve had nothing to do with him creatively. I’m just a HUGE fan.

We are on the precipice of living in a world where the average, casual Marvel fan will now be fully aware of #MoonKnight & how awesome he is. Regardless of how the show turns out, I’m left with an extremely weird feeling. One that is hard to equate an adequate comparison for
